PY  - 2018
T2  - Arthroscopy - Journal of Arthroscopic and Related Surgery
VL  - 34
IS  - 10
SP  - 2782
EP  - 2783
DO  - 10.1016/j.arthro.2018.07.015
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85053831151&doi=10.1016%2fj.arthro.2018.07.015&partnerID=40&md5=4e55d760ff836e466a872cc00d99bb7b
AB  - Failure of rotator cuff repairs may be attributed to biological, mechanical, or rehabilitative reasons. New all-suture anchors have several theoretical benefits that make them potentially attractive for use in rotator cuff repair. As their mechanical strength results from the anchor deploying as a button or molly bolt against the inner cortical bone, it stands to reason that decortication performed for the purposes of improved repair biology may be particularly detrimental to the initial time-zero biomechanics of all-suture anchors. It is unclear whether the statistically significant all-suture biomechanics seen with and without decortication translate clinically. © 2018 Arthroscopy Association of North America
